	<text>
		<body>
			<p><persName>MORRIS NEWBURGER</persName>, <lb/> PRESIDENT.</p>
			<p><persName>MAYER SULZBERGER</persName>, <lb/> CHAIRMAN PUBLICATION COMMITTEE.</p>
			<p><persName>MORRIS DANNENBAUM</persName><lb/> TREASURER.</p>
			<p><persName>C. S. BERNHEIMER</persName>,<lb/> ASSISTANT SECRETARY</p>
			<p rend="align(center)">The Jewish Publication Society of
				<placeName>America</placeName>. <placeName>1015 ARCH STREET, P. O. BOX
					1164</placeName>, <placeName>139 WEST UPSAL ST.,<lb/> GERMANTOWN,
					PHILADA.</placeName>
				<placeName>PHILADELPHIA</placeName>.</p>
			<p rend="align(right)"><date>June, 17, 1896</date>.</p>
			<p><addressee>Judge Mayer Sulzberger</addressee>;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir,</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">I beg leave to send you a copy of<lb/> our correspondence with the
				contemplated English contributors<lb/> to the Bible translation,m and to direct your
				attention to the<lb/> explanatory letter to <persName>Dr. Adler</persName>, (marked
				A) which accompanied<lb/> the Instructions. The fact that this letter was not
				placed<lb/> before the gentlemen who signed the collective letter<lb/> of
				declination of <date>April 6</date>, (marked B) can only be accounted<lb/> for by an
				oversight on the part of the secretary to <persName>Dr. Adler</persName>, for
				it<lb/> was enclosed in the <sic>envelop</sic> with the Instructions addressed<lb/>
				to <persName>Dr. Adler</persName>. A second copy, however, of his letter was in
				the<lb/> hands of the chief Rabbi before the collective letter of<lb/> declination
				(marked B) was sent off as evident from<lb/> the P. S. to the letter (marked C)
				Whether the signers were in-<lb/>formed of this explanatory letter, I have no means
				of<lb/> ascertaining. It would seem that <persName>Mr. Joseph Jacobs</persName>,
				at<lb/> the time of his writing to you upon the matter was<lb/> not aware of its
				existence. You will confer a great favor<lb/> on me if you will kindly undertake to
				convince <persName>Mr. Jacobs</persName>,<lb/> that nothing was neglected on our
				part to show our English<lb/>
				<sic>brethern</sic>, that our making the <persName>Leeser</persName> Bible the
				work-<lb/>ing basis for our enterprise, was not intended to fetter<lb/> the hands of
				the contributors in any way.</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)">Believe me, dear Sir,</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)">Very Truly Yours.</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)">
				<persName role="author">M Jastrow</persName>
			</p>
		</body>
	</text>
